# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: catcher
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the years 1845 to 1868 throughout the world.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] At its December 1868 annual meeting, the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP) permitted professional clubs.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] Twelve existing members did "go pro" and constitute the professional field for 1869.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1868 season records for 98 teams, many of them incomplete ("(inc)" in the table).
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 15 of that season's teams "major" (not marked).
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors" (not marked), all of the 1869 "pros" (*), all 14 member clubs with at least twelve wins on record, and a few others.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] For the seven listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] At least four Association clubs not listed here would someday try professionalism: Riverside of Portsmouth, Ohio (1870); Kekionga of Fort Wayne, Indiana (1871); Middletown of Mansfield, Connecticut (1872); Resolute of Elizabeth, New Jersey (1873).
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] Meanwhile, only two brand new professional baseball clubs would be established in the next three years, the Chicago White Stockings for 1870 and the Boston Red Stockings for 1871.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] Their commercial origins may be related to their survival alone by 1877, and on to 2010, while all of their rivals with older and amateur roots fell away.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1867 season records for 89 teams, many of them incomplete ("(inc)" in the table).
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 17 of that season's teams "major" (not marked).
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors", all 13 member clubs with at least fourteen wins on record, and a few others.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] For the nine listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] Star (*) marks ten clubs among twelve who would go pro in 1869.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] Excelsior of Chicago and Buckeye of Cincinnati are listed because they were probably the strongest teams in the west after the Cincinnati Red Stockings.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1866 season records for 58 of 93 association members, said to be complete for games between two member clubs.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 20 of that season's teams "major" including three old New York rivals of the Knickerbockers.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors", all 14 members with at least eight wins on record, and a few others.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] For the fifteen listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] Star (*) marks eight clubs among twelve who would go pro in 1869, three seasons later.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] For the preceding 1865 season Marshall Wright lists 30 members with supposedly complete records for most of them.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] Twenty-two of the thirty were in Greater New York.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 19 teams "major" in the first season that he covers: sixteen of the members and three others (Lowell, Harvard, and Camden).
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] No one traveled much and membership was still depressed by the Civil War.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] There had been 59 delegates at the March 1860 annual meeting, and 55 at the next annual meeting that December (on a new baseball calendar), who thereby intended to play during the 1861 season that the war curtailed.
[src:catcher/1858-in-baseball] Nine of 59 and eleven of 55 were from outside Greater New York.
[src:catcher/1877-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1877 throughout the world.
[src:catcher/1884-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1884 throughout the world.
[src:catcher/1884-in-baseball] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:catcher/1884-in-baseball] Old Hoss Radbourn won a record 59 or 60 games (depending on the sources), a record that will almost certainly never be broken.
[src:catcher/1884-in-baseball] In addition to wins, Radbourn led the National League in games (75), games started (73), complete games (73), ERA (1.38), saves (2), strikeouts (441), and innings pitched (678.2).
[src:catcher/1884-in-baseball] The season record for pitching strikeouts (369, by Tim Keefe 1883) is broken by seven players, with Hugh Daily beating Keefe's record by 114.
[src:catcher/1884-in-baseball] To this day (as of 2020), six of the top ten strikeout seasons were accomplished in 1884 (including five of the top seven).
[src:catcher/1884-in-baseball] 1884 was the first season in which pitchers were allowed to throw overhand.
[src:catcher/1888-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1888 throughout the world.
[src:catcher/1901-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1901 throughout the world.
[src:catcher/1907-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1907 throughout the world.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The **2017 Houston Astros season** was the 56th season for the Major League Baseball (MLB) franchise located in Houston, Texas, their 53rd as the Astros, fifth in both the American League (AL) and AL West division, and 18th at Minute Maid Park.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] They entered the season as having posted an 84–78 record, in third place and 11 games behind the division-champion Texas Rangers.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Dallas Keuchel made his third consecutive Opening Day start on April 3 for Houston, who hosted the Seattle Mariners and won, 3–0.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros' first-round draft pick in the amateur draft was pitcher J.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Bukauskas; they also chose outfielders Jake Meyers and Chas McCormick in the 13th and 21st rounds, respectively.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros sent six players to the 88th All-Star Game, including second baseman Jose Altuve, center fielder George Springer, shortstop Carlos Correa, and pitchers Keuchel, Lance McCullers Jr., and Chris Devenski.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] First baseman Jeff Bagwell, who had spent his entire 15-year major league career with Houston, became the second inductee into the Baseball Hall of Fame as an Astro.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Near the end of August, the Astros acquired pitcher Justin Verlander at the trade deadline, who won his first five starts.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Meanwhile, as Hurricane Harvey impacted Greater Houston, the Astros relocated their August 29–31 series with the Rangers from Minute Maid Park to Tropicana Field in St.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Following the storm, Astros personnel assisted with rebuilding and charitable efforts around Houston.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] On September 17, the Astros clinched the AL West with a 7–1 victory over the Seattle, for their first AL West division title, eighth division title overall, and 11th postseason qualification.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros defeated the Boston Red Sox, 3–2, on September 29 to claim their 100th win of the season for their first 100-win season since 1998.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Following the regular season, the Astros met the Red Sox at home in the American League Division Series (ALDS), and defeated them in four games.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Houston then advanced to the American League Championship Series (ALCS) and defeated the New York Yankees in seven games for their first AL pennant.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] After going 2–0 with a 0.56 earned run average (ERA) and 21 strikeouts, Verlander was named ALCS Most Valuable Player (MVP).
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The pennant was Houston's first since winning the National League (NL) pennant in 2005.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros' season culminated with the first World Series championship in franchise history, winning in seven games over the Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Springer, who tied a World Series record with five home runs, was named World Series MVP.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The 2017 Astros featured the highest-scoring offense in the major leagues (896 runs), the highest batting average (.282), on-base percentage (.346), and slugging percentage (.478).
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] AL batting champion Jose Altuve (.346) won a number of distinctions, including Most Valuable Player (AL MVP), *Sports Illustrated* Sportsperson of the Year, and Associated Press Male Athlete of the Year.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Altuve joined Bagwell as the second Astro to win the MVP, winning it in 1994.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Because of its record-setting numbers and individual accolades, this Astros batting lineup is often cited as one of the highest-performing in history.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The season was later marred by a sign stealing scandal that ultimately led to significant backlash from baseball fans, the loss of draft picks and a record setting fine from the MLB, and the dismissal of employees in the organization that were directly linked to the scandal.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros concluded the 2016 season with an 84–78 (.519) record, in third place in the AL West division, and 11 games behind the division-champion Texas Rangers.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In the Wild Card standings, Houston trailed the Baltimore Orioles and Toronto Blue Jays by five games, thus missing a playoff entrance.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] With an 86–76 (.531) regular-season record in 2015, Houston registered 84 or more victories over consecutive seasons for the first time since 2001 to 2005, when they were still members of the National League.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The 2016 season was the final in which Houston would miss the playoffs until 2025.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros commenced the 2017 regular season on April 3 on Opening Day, at home hosting the Seattle Mariners.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Dallas Keuchel made his third consecutive Opening Day start for the Astros, with Félix Hernández as his counterpart.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] George Springer led off the Astros' offensive season with a home run.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] During the fourth inning, Carlos Correa homered.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In the bottom of the sixth, Alex Bregman drew a leadoff base on balls, advanced to third on Jose Altuve's line drive single, and scored on Correa's sacrifice fly.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Meanwhile, Keuchel remained in complete control, tossing seven two-hit shutout frames, two walks, and earned a game score of 75.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Keuchel also earned the win while leading the Astros to a 3–0 decision.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Luke Gregerson pitched the eighth inning to receive credit for the hold, and Ken Giles closed out the ninth to convert the save.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Correa's home run on Opening Day was his second consecutive,. while Springer's home run was the first of his career on Opening Day, and tenth leadoff.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The triumph was the fifth in succession on Opening Day for Houston, tying the club record set in 1977, and continuing into a winning streak of ten through 2022.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] One of the most memorable and debated manifestations to hallmark the 2017 season was Jose Altuve's height and style of play contrasts with that of New York Yankees right fielder Aaron Judge.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] At 6 feet 7 inches (2.01 m) and 280 pounds (130 kg), Judge was a rookie who emerged as his chief rival in the 2017 American League (AL) Most Valuable Player (MVP) race, eventually breaking the record for both home runs hit (52) and walks drawn (127) by a rookie while leading the AL.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In July, a photo emerged of the pair standing side by side in game versus the Yankees that displayed their drastic size difference and became a viral phenomenon.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Two Astros pitchers were awarded the AL Pitcher of the Month Award in the first two months of the season.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In April, left-handed starting pitcher Dallas Keuchel posted a 5–0 win–loss record (W–L), allowing six runs in six games started and 1.21 earned run average (ERA) over 44+2⁄3 innings pitched (IP).
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] It was his fourth career monthly award, making him the first Astros pitcher to win four; J.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Richard was the other Astros pitcher who had won three.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Keuchel joined Bartolo Colón, Félix Hernández, Justin Verlander as active pitchers who had won at least four.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] On May 4, the Astros tied a then-club record for a nine-inning game with 16 runners left on base (LOB) during a 10–4 defeat to the versus Texas Rangers.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] This was the 24th game in club history played in 9 innings or fewer in which the Astros collected at least 10 hits and 10 walks each, and just the third that ended in a loss.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] From May 6−23, starting pitcher Lance McCullers Jr. completed a scoreless innings streak of 22, which among Astros pitchers, was the longest scoreless inning streak since Roy Oswalt delivered 32 from August 27 through September 11, 2008.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In that same span, McCullers also became the first Astros pitcher since Nolan Ryan in 1984 to allow no earned runs over at least five innings pitched in each of four consecutive appearances.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] During the May 14 game versus New York at Yankee Stadium, third baseman Alex Bregman hit his first major league grand slam off Masahiro Tanaka in a 10–7 Astros win.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] On May 20, Keuchel was placed on the 10-day disabled list due to a pinched nerve in his neck.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Facing an 8–2 deficit on May 29, the Astros engineered an epic comeback by exploding for 11 runs in the eighth and ninth innings to outlast the Minnesota Twins, 16 to 8.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Carlos Beltrán led the way, slugging a home run, and collecting four of Houston's 18 hits.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Jose Altuve, Carlos Correa, and Marwin González each tallied three safeties.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] This was Beltrán's third four-hit bout as a member of the Astros, and first since October 11, 2004, during Game 5 of the National League Division Series (NLDS).
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Shortstop Carlos Correa delivered a career-best five consecutive multiple-hit games from May 25−29, and totaled 14 such games on the month.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In May, he was selected for his first AL Player of the Month Award, and McCullers his first AL Pitcher of the Month Award.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In 26 games, Correa batted .386, eight doubles, seven home runs, 26 RBI and a 1.130 OPS.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] His batting average and RBI total led the AL, on-base percentage ranked third, hits and OPS fifth, and slugging tied for sixth.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] McCullers was credited with a 4−0 record in six starts during the month of May.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] He permitted an AL-leading 0.99 earned run average (ERA), 21 hits, and a .164 batting average against (BAA) with 37 strikeouts.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] He also ranked second in wins, third in BAA, and tied for fifth in strikeouts.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] With persistent neck problems, the Astros placed Keuchel back on the disabled list on June 8.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] On June 14, Derek Fisher homered and collected an RBI single for his first hits, both as part of an Astros' 9-run sixth inning to lead a defeat the Texas Rangers, 13–2.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Fisher became the first major leaguer to get his first two hits in the same inning since Adam LaRoche did so on June 7, 2004, for the Atlanta Braves.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Jake Marisnick also homered for the Astros, whose hitting gave Francis Martes (1–0) his first major league win, also making his first major league start.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In the July 9 game versus the Toronto Blue Jays, the Astros won 19–1 as Correa homered twice, collected four hits, and drove in a career-best five runs.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] He reached the 20-home run mark and saw a 15-game hitting streak snapped the previous day.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] It was the Astros' 60th win of the season, making them the fifth team within the previous 40 years to reach that many wins before the All-Star break.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros entered the All-Star break with the best record in the AL, at 60–29, marking the best 89-game start in franchise history.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Their 16+1⁄2-game lead in the AL West marked the largest divisional lead the club had ever attained all-time.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] For the first time in franchise history, three Astros players were elected by fans as starters for the All-Star Game, held at Marlins Park in Miami.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The starters were Altuve, Correa, and center fielder George Springer.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] As was former Astros manager Brad Mills' selection, Altuve, who typically hit third for the Astros, batted leadoff for the American League.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Springer, the Astros leadoff hitter, batted cleanup.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Two others Astros made the team, including Keuchel and McCullers.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] On July 18, Correa sustained a torn ligament in the left thumb, and the Astros placed him on the DL.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Rookie third baseman Colin Moran sustained fractures of the facial bones during a game versus the Baltimore Orioles on July 22.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The injury occurred as he fouled off a pitch, and the batted ball struck him directly in the face.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] He underwent surgery to repair the fractures on July 31.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] George Springer was placed on the diabled list (DL) on July 28 due to left quadriceps discomfort.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] On July 30, 2017, former Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, New York.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In July, Altuve batted .485 for the fifth-highest average in one month since 1961.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Over 23 games, he accumulated 48 hits, 10 doubles, one triple, four home runs, 21 RBI and 1.251 OPS.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] He carried a 19-game hitting streak from July 2–23.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] He also recorded five consecutive multi-hit games during the week of July 3–9, becoming the ninth player in MLB history to do so.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] His average set the Astros record for one calendar month—surpassing Richard Hidalgo's .476 average in September of 2000—and he won his second AL Player of the Month Award.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Yuli Gurriel won the AL Rookie of the Month Award in July, and he led all AL rookies with .565 slugging percentage, .899 OPS, 28 hits, nine doubles, and 20 RBI.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The nine doubles tied Lance Berkman's club record for rookies in a single month.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Carlos Beltrán, who served primarily as the designated hitter for Houston this season, made his final career appearance on defense on August 5.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] He played left field for the first nine innings of 10-inning loss to the Toronto Blue Jays.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] On August 10, Bregman tied the Astros' record for extra-base hits in consecutive games at 10 games, first accomplished by Hidalgo.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In a 27-game stretch following the All-Star break, the Astros slumped, going 11–16 (.407).
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] On August 13, 2017, the Chicago White Sox traded reliever Tyler Clippard to the Astros for a player to be named later or cash considerations.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] On August 19, Gurriel tied an American League record for first basemen, becoming the seventh to participate in six double plays.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] On Saturday, August 26, Hurricane Harvey reached Houston.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros were playing a series on the read versus the Los Angeles Angels at the time, and were scheduled to return home to host the Texas Rangers.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The games versus the Rangers were relocated to Tropicana Field in St.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Petersburg, Florida, as more than 50 inches of rain inundated parts of Greater Houston and flooded more than one-third.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Team officials planned for the next series versus the New York Mets also to be played at Tropicana Field, but mayor Sylvester Turner encouraged Astros president Reid Ryan to return the team to Houston to play the Mets.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] "You guys come home and play baseball," said Turner to Ryan.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Having lost 17 of 27 games as of August 31 (.370 winning percentage), the Astros acquired right-handed ace and former Cy Young Award winner Justin Verlander from the Detroit Tigers just moments before the trade deadline.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Detroit received prospects Franklin Pérez, Jake Rogers, and Daz Cameron.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros also claimed outfielder Cameron Maybin off waivers from the Angels on August 31.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Correa and McCullers returned from the disabled list at that time.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Verlander won all five regular season starts in an Astros uniform to help lead them to a 22–8 record over their final month and an overall registry of 101–61, clinching the AL West division title.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] After the Astros returned to Houston and the New York Mets and MLB agreed to do a Saturday day–night doubleheader, the Astros spent the first Friday of the month surveying the aftermath and visiting with hurricane evacuees.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] This portended an emotional return to Minute Maid Park, with many evacuees in attendance for the doubleheader.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Hinch addressed the crowd, "Hello, Houston.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] It's good to be home," adding that it was "a very special day for us to start the rebuild process of our great city." The Mets starter, coincidentally named Matt Harvey, surrendered seven runs in two innings in the first game as the Astros swept the doubleheader, 12–8, and 4–1.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Springer also hit a two run home run in the second inning of Game 1.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Between games, the Astros and fans received a preview of Verlander's pitching while he tossed a bullpen session.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In the aftermath of Hurricane Harvey, the Astros continue to assist in the rebuild of various parts of the city during their off-time.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] One establishment included the Houston chapter of the Boys & Girls Clubs of America.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Individual members of the team delivered meals, cleaned up damaged homes, and rescued pets.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Brown Convention Center, which housed more than 7,000 people displaced from their homes.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Verlander's debut as an Astro occurred on September 5 in a 3–1 victory versus the Mariners.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The only run he allowed was a home run to Kyle Seager and he struck out seven over six innings.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Maybin homered in the seventh inning to break a 1–1 tie, giving the Astros their sixth consecutive win.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Moran returned to the Astros on September 19, having completed a rehabilitation assignment at Class-A Quad Cities River Bandits.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] He had sustained a fracture below the left eye in a game on July 22.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] On September 19, Altuve was announced as the recipient of MLB's Lou Gehrig Memorial Award for 2017, as the player "who best exemplifies the giving character" of Gehrig.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In the last series of the regular season, the Astros defeated the Red Sox 3–2 on September 29 for their 100th win of the season.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Charlie Morton (14–7) pitched six innings to earn the win and Bregman hit a tie-breaking home run.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros joined the Los Angeles Dodgers and Cleveland Indians as 100-game winners in 2017, marking the first time since 2003 that three or more teams reached the milestone, and the sixth time overall in major league history.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] It was Houston's first 100-win season since 1998, when they won a club-record 102 games.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros defeated the Boston Red Sox on the final day of the regular season, Sunday, Oct.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] 1, 2017, to finish the season with a record of 101–61.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Overall, Houston finished the 2017 regular season with a 101–61 record, at the time the second-highest win total in franchise history, for a .623 winning percentage, trailing the 1998 team by one win.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The 1998 and 2017 campaigns represented the first two having attained 100 victories for the Astros.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Having achieved 200 hits on the season, Altuve became just the fifth hitter since integration in 1947 to record four straight 200-hit seasons, following Wade Boggs (1983−89), Kirby Puckett (1986−89), Ichiro Suzuki (2001−2010), and Michael Young (2003−07).
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] He also became the first hitter in Major League history to solely lead his respective league in hits for four years in a row while also collecting his third career batting title.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Suzuki technically led the AL in hits from 2006 to 2010, but tied with Dustin Pedroia in 2008.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] As winners of their respective division, the Astros received a bye during the procession of the AL Wild Card Game, played between the wild card winners, New York Yankees and Minnesota Twins.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros were seeded #2 in the AL, the result of attaining the second-most wins in the league.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Their first playoff game of 2017 was in the American League Division Series, versus the Boston Red Sox.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] It was the first time the Astros had faced the Red Sox in the postseason.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros played American League East division champion Boston Red Sox in the ALDS.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In Game 1, Altuve hit three home runs in a single game for the first time of his career while becoming the tenth player to hit three home runs in a single postseason game.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Verlander won two games in the Astros' 3-games-to-1 triumph over the Red Sox.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] He started and won Game 1, and picked up the second win with 2+2⁄3 innings of relief in the clinching Game 4.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros faced the wild-card game winning Yankees in the ALCS.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros selected Keuchel to start Game 1 versus the Yankees' Masahiro Tanaka.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In a pitcher's duel, Tanaka allowed no runs through the first three innings before the Astros scored in the bottom of the fourth.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Altuve hit an infield single and stole second base before Carlos Correa drove him in with an RBI single.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Yuli Gurriel drove in Correa to give the Astros a 2–0 lead.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Keuchel recorded ten strikeouts, allowing four hits and no runs in seven innings.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Tanaka pitched six innings with three strikeouts and allowed two earned runs.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Yankees scored their only run of the game in the ninth, when closer Ken Giles allowed a solo home run to Greg Bird before striking out Jacoby Ellsbury swinging to end the game.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Giles struck out four of six batters faced for his first save of the ALCS and second of the postseason.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] On October 14, Verlander started Game 2, throwing a 13-strikeout, 2–1 complete game victory.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros won the game on a ninth-inning walk-off double by Carlos Correa that drove home Altuve.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Facing elimination in Game 6 of the ALCS, Verlander pitched seven shutout innings in a 7−1 victory over the Yankees.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros also defeated the Yankees 4−0 in Game 7, on October 21, 2017, allowing them to advance to the World Series for the second time in franchise history, and first as a member of the American League.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] McCullers pitched four scoreless innings in relief to earn his first career save.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Verlander's totals in the ALCS included a 2−0 W−L, 0.56 ERA and 21 strikeouts in 16 innings pitched.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] As a result, he was named the ALCS Most Valuable Player (MVP).
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In Game 2, Springer, Correa, Altuve—and two Dodgers players–Charlie Culberson and Yasiel Puig—all homered in extra innings as the Astros prevailed, 7−6.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The five home runs accounted for the most hit in extra innings of any single game in major league history.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In Game 3, Yu Darvish started for the Dodgers against Lance McCullers Jr. for the Astros.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros scored four runs in the bottom of the second inning on a home run by Yuli Gurriel and RBIs by González, Brian McCann, and Alex Bregman.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Darvish left the game after 1+2⁄3 innings, which is the shortest outing of his career (he would tie that feat in Game 7, that time giving up five runs).
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In the top of the third, McCullers loaded the bases with three consecutive walks.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Dodgers managed to score one run when Corey Seager grounded into a double play.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros added another run in the fifth on an RBI single by Evan Gattis and the Dodgers added two in the sixth on an RBI groundout by Puig and a wild pitch.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] McCullers wound up pitching 51⁄3 innings and allowed three runs on four hits.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Brad Peacock replaced McCullers, completing the final 3+2⁄3 innings with no hits allowed and four strikeouts to earn his first major league save.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] It was the longest hitless World Series relief outing since Ron Taylor's four innings in Game 4 of the 1964 Series, and tied Ken Clay for the longest hitless postseason save, first accomplished in the 1978 ALCS.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Game 5 featured a "roller coaster" of momentum changes induced by key home runs.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] The Astros fell behind by scores of 4–0, 7–4, and 8–7, but hit a game-tying home run to reduce each deficit.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] They eventually led 12–9 in the ninth inning, but the Dodgers made their own comeback to tie the game at 12 with a home run from Puig and an RBI single from Chris Taylor.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In the bottom of the 10th, Alex Bregman singled to left field off Dodgers closer Kenley Jansen to score pinch runner Derek Fisher for the walk-off hit.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] That single concluded the second-longest game in World Series history, running at five hours, 17 minutes.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Doug Miller of MLB.com ranked World Series Game 5 as the top game of 2017.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Springer homered and doubled in Game 7, finishing with two runs and two RBI.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] He hit five home runs, tying the World Series record shared by Reggie Jackson and Dodgers second baseman Chase Utley.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] He also homered in each of the final four games, setting a World Series record for consecutive games with a home run.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Springer was named the World Series Most Valuable Player (MVP), hitting 11 of 29 at bats and driving in seven as the Astros' leadoff hitter.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] As a side note, Springer was featured on a 2014 cover of *Sports Illustrated* magazine that heralded a World Series win for the Astros in 2017.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Altuve and Verlander were named co-winners of the Babe Ruth Award as MVPs of the Astros' postseason.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] In the Astros' 18-game championship run, Altuve batted .310/.388/.634, 22 hits, 14 runs scored, seven home runs, 14 RBI, and nine extra-base hits.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] He established a franchise record for total hits in a postseason.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Further, he tied the record for home runs by a second baseman in a single postseason, and hit the fourth-most among all players.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Verlander made six appearances and five starts, being credited with a 4–1 record, and gaining a 2.21 ERA, .177 batting average against, eight walks, and 38 strikeouts in 36+2⁄3 innings.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Weeks after the end of the World Series, an unidentified Astros player revealed that Darvish was tipping his pitches.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] He cycled through 3+1⁄3 IP in two World Series starts and allowed a 21.60 ERA, while striking out no Houston batters.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] He was much more successful in the NLDS and NLCS, allowing two earned runs over 11+1⁄3 IP with 14 strikeouts.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Altuve, along with Houston Texans defensive end J.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Watt, were named co-winners of the *Sports Illustrated* Sportsperson of the Year Award for his efforts in leading the Astros to their first World Series title and aiding in the recovery of the Greater Houston area in the aftermath of Hurricane Harvey.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p01] Following the conclusion of the World Series, Beltrán announced his retirement from his professional baseball.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p02] Two years later in November 2019, allegations were made that the Astros used a sophisticated electronic sign stealing system.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p02] *The Athletic* published a report which stated that Mike Fiers, who left the Astros after 2017 and later played for the Detroit Tigers and Oakland Athletics, warned his new teams about the practice.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p02] The Athletic article heavily stressed that the illegal sign stealing was hardly exclusive to the Astros, but was in fact rampant across Major League Baseball.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p02] An MLB investigation into the allegations was launched following the report.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p02] Baseball YouTuber Jomboy Media was also one of the first to bring this to public attention, adding that a banging sound could be heard before each pitch.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p02] The number of bangs indicated to Astros batters what pitches were expected to be thrown from opposing pitchers.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p02] On January 13, 2020, Major League Baseball handed down punishments for the Astros ballclub in reference to the sign stealing allegations.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p02] Both general manager Jeff Luhnow and manager A.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p02] Hinch were suspended for the entirety of the 2020 season, and the club was fined $5 million and forced to forfeit first and second round draft picks of the 2020 and 2021 drafts.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p02] This punishment is a record for such an infringement.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p02] The $5 million fine is the highest allowed by the MLB Constitution.
[src:catcher/2017-houston-astros-season-p02] As a consequence of MLB's announcement, Luhnow and Hinch were promptly fired by Astros' owner Jim Crane the same day.
[src:catcher/catcher] Positioned behind home plate and facing toward the outfield, the catcher can see the whole field and is therefore in the best position to direct and lead the other players in a defensive play.
[src:catcher/catcher] The catcher typically calls for pitches using PitchCom, or hand signals.
[src:catcher/catcher] The calls are based on the pitcher's mechanics and strengths, as well as the batter's tendencies and weaknesses.
[src:catcher/catcher] Essentially, the catcher controls what happens during the game when the ball is not "in play".
[src:catcher/catcher] Foul tips, bouncing balls in the dirt and contact with runners during plays at the plate are all events to be handled by the catcher, necessitating the use of protective equipment.
[src:catcher/catcher] This includes a mask, chest and throat protectors, shin guards, and a heavily padded catcher's mitt.
[src:catcher/catcher] Though rare, some chest protectors may extend lower to provide some shield to the genitalia; wearing a pelvic protector or cup, depending on the case, is preferred and more common.
[src:catcher/catcher] The physical and mental demands of being involved in every defensive play can wear catchers down over a long season, and can have a negative effect on their offensive output.
[src:catcher/catcher] Because of the strategic defensive importance of catching, if a catcher has exceptional defensive skills, teams are often willing to overlook their relative offensive weaknesses.
[src:catcher/catcher] A knowledgeable catcher's ability to work with the pitcher, via pitch selection and location, can diminish the effectiveness of the opposing team's offense.
[src:catcher/catcher] Many great defensive catchers toiled in relative anonymity, because they did not produce large offensive numbers.
[src:catcher/catcher] Notable examples of light-hitting, defensive specialists were Jerry Grote, Jeff Mathis, Martín Maldonado, Ray Schalk, Jim Hegan, Jim Sundberg and Brad Ausmus.
[src:catcher/catcher] Schalk's career batting average of .253 is the lowest of any position player in the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:catcher/catcher] His selection for enshrinement in 1955 was largely a tribute to his outstanding defensive skills.
[src:catcher/catcher] In the numbering system used to record baseball plays, the catcher is assigned the number '2'.
[src:catcher/catcher] In the middle of the nineteenth century, the game of baseball began to evolve from a sport played by amateurs for recreation into a more serious game played by professionals.
[src:catcher/catcher] One of the most dramatic changes was the transition of the pitcher's delivery from an underhand motion to an overhanded throw.
[src:catcher/catcher] Before the American Civil War, the pitcher's role was to initiate the action by offering an underhanded throw to the batter, in much the same way that a basketball referee offers up a jump ball to begin play.
[src:catcher/catcher] Since this type of pitching often caused the batter to hit lazy, foul pop-ups, catchers played their position approximately twenty to twenty-five feet behind the batter, and wore no protective equipment.
[src:catcher/catcher] As the game progressed towards professionals and became more serious, pitchers began to attempt to prevent the batter from hitting the ball by throwing faster pitches.
[src:catcher/catcher] With the introduction of the called strike in 1858, catchers began inching closer to home plate due to the rules requirement that a strikeout could only be completed by a catch.
[src:catcher/catcher] The rules governing the delivery of pitches proved to be hard to enforce, and pitchers continued to stretch the boundaries of the rules until the 1870s when the release point of pitches had reached the pitcher's waist level.
[src:catcher/catcher] Pitchers had begun throwing overhand by 1884, when the National League made a rule change removing all restrictions on the pitcher's delivery.
[src:catcher/catcher] These developments meant that catchers began to take on a crucial defensive role, as a pitcher's deceptive deliveries could only be effective if the catcher was capable of fielding them.
[src:catcher/catcher] The progression of the catcher positioning themselves closer to the plate would lead to changes in pitching deliveries that would revolutionize the sport.
[src:catcher/catcher] In the 1870s, pitcher Candy Cummings was able to introduce the curveball because his catcher, Nat Hicks, fielded his position in close proximity to home plate and was able to catch the deceptive pitch.
[src:catcher/catcher] Other specialized pitches such as the spitball and the knuckleball followed, which further emphasized the defensive importance of the catcher's position.
[src:catcher/catcher] At about the same time that catchers began fielding their position closer to home plate, baseball teams began using a less rubbery ball which led to a decline in the number of runs scored.
[src:catcher/catcher] In the 1860s it was common for teams to score fifty or sixty runs in a game.
[src:catcher/catcher] The combination of the new, harder ball and the continuation of the rise in pitcher's release points helped usher in what became known as the Dead-ball era.
[src:catcher/catcher] The decrease in run production placed greater significance on stolen bases and bunts, which in turn emphasized the crucial defensive role played by catchers.
[src:catcher/catcher] In 1901, the National League introduced a new rule specifying that the catcher must stand within 10 feet of home plate.
[src:catcher/catcher] The American League adopted the rule the following year.
[src:catcher/catcher] The rising velocity of pitches in conjunction with catchers gradually moving closer to home plate significantly increased the risk of injuries for catchers, especially face and hand injuries.
[src:catcher/catcher] By the late 1870s, catchers began to use padded, fingerless gloves to protect their hands, and in 1877 the first protective catcher's mask was used.
[src:catcher/catcher] The first catchers to use protective masks sometimes had their courage called into question, but the effectiveness of the masks in preventing injuries meant that they became widely accepted.
[src:catcher/catcher] In the 1880s, the first padded chest protectors came into use, and in 1888 specialized catcher's mitts used on the non-throwing hand began to be used.
[src:catcher/catcher] Schenck of Princeton University was the first to use chest protectors when he stuffed copies of The Daily Princetonian under his shirt during a game against Harvard University.
[src:catcher/catcher] A Boston sporting goods company noticed his innovation and began producing the wearable chest pads.
[src:catcher/catcher] The final pieces of protective gear were shin guards which were first worn by catcher Roger Bresnahan in 1907.
[src:catcher/catcher] Together, the rules changes and the new protective equipment transformed the catcher's defensive role to the way that it is presently played.
[src:catcher/catcher] The catcher is usually the first to notice the tendencies, quirks, and peculiarities of each home-plate umpire.
[src:catcher/catcher] Some umpires favor high strikes, pitched balls that are technically above the strike zone but appear, to the umpire, to be good.
[src:catcher/catcher] Conversely, some umpires will call low pitches strikes even when they are slightly below the knees.
[src:catcher/catcher] Other umpires have an inside bias or an outside bias; some umpires have more than one bias; some are uniformly lenient; some have very restricted notions of the strike zone, and the pitcher will constantly feel that their pitches are unfairly judged.
[src:catcher/catcher] The catcher can exploit an umpire's tendencies by taking them into account in when receiving the ball.
[src:catcher/catcher] The catcher can help their pitcher get more strike calls from the umpire by using a technique called "framing".
[src:catcher/catcher] This practice is a matter of a catcher keeping the mitt inside the strike zone, or making the pitch appear as close to the strike zone, when receiving the pitch, thereby giving the plate umpire the impression that the pitch is in the strike zone, even if it is not.
[src:catcher/catcher] When framing, a catcher will also hold their mitt still for a second or two so that the umpire has an opportunity to thoroughly consider their call (and, hopefully, let their innate biases influence their decision in a direction favorable to the catcher's team).
[src:catcher/catcher] The catcher, when receiving a borderline pitch, usually has several options in how they make the catch.
[src:catcher/catcher] They can catch the pitch in the webbing of their mitt or in the heel; they can catch the pitch on their forehand or backhand, as necessary; they can catch a low pitch with the mitt pointed upward or downward.
[src:catcher/catcher] These choices help the catcher to create a favorable presentation (or frame) for the umpire.
[src:catcher/catcher] A variation on "framing" is called "pulling pitches".
[src:catcher/catcher] The general approach is to catch the half of the ball that is outside the strike zone and show the umpire only the half of the ball, lodged in the mitt, that is closer to the zone.
[src:catcher/catcher] The illusion is often enhanced with a slight 'tug' of the mitt (of an inch or two) toward the strike zone.
[src:catcher/catcher] By rule, the catcher must station directly back of the plate (generally in the catcher's box) the moment a pitch is thrown but may leave at any time to catch a pitch or make a play.
[src:catcher/catcher] The moment an intentional ball leaves a pitcher's hand, the catcher must have both feet in the catcher's box.
[src:catcher/catcher] The catcher is the only defensive player who is allowed to be in foul territory when a pitch is thrown.
[src:catcher/catcher] A catcher's balk occurs when the catcher is not properly set in the designated box.
[src:catcher/catcher] Once the pitcher releases the ball and the catcher is caught outside of this zone, the play is thrown out.
[src:catcher/catcher] The term "catcher's balk" is not official, but it is common to hear among catchers and umpires alike.
[src:catcher/catcher] If a pitch is thrown and the catcher has extended their arm resulting in the catcher's glove being contacted by the batter's swinging bat, a catcher's interference is called, and the batter is awarded first base.
[src:catcher/catcher] If the bases were loaded, it results in a run being scored, but since it is an error, the batter is not credited with a run batted in.
[src:catcher/catcher] The catcher's interference call is uncommon.
[src:catcher/catcher] Also, an interference penalty may be declined by the batting team, such as when a better result ensues.
[src:catcher/catcher] To block balls that a pitcher throws on a bounce toward home plate (pitches that are said to be "in the dirt"), the catcher will slide their body to the left or right, as necessary, to place themselves directly in the path of the ball.
[src:catcher/catcher] Once in position, they push towards the ball while dropping to their knees, place their mitt between their legs to prevent the ball from passing through, and lean forward to deaden the rebound when, and if, the ball bounces off their thigh or torso.
[src:catcher/catcher] Although inexperienced catchers may try to catch the errant pitch with the mitt, coaches often prioritize the catcher's ability to "keep the ball in front of the body" than to make a catch with their mitt.
[src:catcher/catcher] Ideally, the catcher will be able to knock the ball to the ground where it will stop within arm's reach.
[src:catcher/catcher] To perform this properly, without the ball being deflected in an undesirable direction, the catcher must angle their body so that their chest is always leaning forward, toward home plate.
[src:catcher/catcher] Tucking your chin or looking the ball in will help with deadening the ball like this.
[src:catcher/catcher] This maneuver is often difficult, and its difficulty depends largely on how fast the ball is traveling, the angle at which the ball is thrown into the ground, where it first hits the ground, the firmness of the ground it hits, and the manner in which it is spinning.
[src:catcher/catcher] As of April 2011 15 of 30 Major League Baseball managers were former catchers.
[src:catcher/catcher] Because catchers are considered a captain on the field (and some, such as Thurman Munson and Jason Varitek were in fact team captains), they are often in charge of planning defensive plays; thus, the catcher will give signs to the pitcher for what pitch is to be thrown.
[src:catcher/catcher] Calling the game refers to the act of catchers deciding the type of pitch delivered to home plate.
[src:catcher/catcher] The responsibility for selecting the type of pitch was traditionally made by the catcher.
[src:catcher/catcher] It is not unusual for a catcher to briefly look at the posture and position of the batter-in-turn prior to calling the next pitch; even the way a batter holds the bat may shed some indication of what the strategy may be.
[src:catcher/catcher] The selection of which pitch to use can depend on a wide variety of situations such as the type of hitter that is being faced, whether there are any base runners, how many outs have been made in the inning, or the current score, among others.
[src:catcher/catcher] Since a catcher uses their fingers to signal and communicate with the pitcher, they may wear colorful stickers on their nails to accentuate the motion of the fingers and thus help with the visibility of the signal.
[src:catcher/catcher] As an alternative, the catcher may wear painted nails, such as with fluorescent polish.
[src:catcher/catcher] Starting in 2022, Major League catchers began wearing a PitchCom device on their wrist.
[src:catcher/catcher] This was done in an attempt to curb the prevalence of sign stealing, which reached its peak after the Houston Astros were caught stealing signs during their World Series-winning 2017 season.
[src:catcher/catcher] In addition, a lefty's throw would tend to come in on the shortstop side of the bag, while a righty's throw would be on the second base side of the bag, which is where the runner is coming in.
[src:catcher/catcher] Consequently, players who are left-handed rarely play catcher.
[src:catcher/catcher] Left-handed catchers have only caught eleven big-league games since 1902, and Jack Clements, who played for 17 years at the end of the nineteenth century, is the only man in the history of baseball to play more than three hundred games as a left-handed catcher.
[src:catcher/catcher] However, some observers, including the famed statistician Bill James and ESPN writer Rob Neyer, have suggested that the real reason that there are no left-handed catchers is because left-handed players with strong throwing arms are almost always encouraged, at an early age, to become pitchers.
[src:catcher/catcher] Benny Distefano, the last lefty thrower to catch a big-league game (in 1989), noted that lefty catchers have difficulty on bunts up the third base line and on fielding throws home for plays at the plate.
[src:catcher/catcher] Others suggest that fielding bunts up the 3rd base line would give the catcher a better throw to 1st base or 2nd base.
[src:catcher/catcher] Unlike the other fielders, the catcher and pitcher must start every play in a designated area.
[src:catcher/catcher] The catcher must be behind home plate in the catcher's box, while the pitcher must be on the pitcher's mound, with one foot in contact with the pitcher's rubber.
[src:catcher/catcher] Once the ball is in play, however, the catcher and pitcher, like the other fielders, can respond to any part of the field necessary to make or assist in a defensive play.
[src:catcher/catcher] In certain game situations, typically a ball batted to the shortstop or third baseman with no runners on base, **the catcher may be expected to back-up first base in case the first baseman misses or mishandles a throw**.
[src:catcher/catcher] Any failure by the catcher can have dire consequences for their team.
[src:catcher/catcher] Passed balls are possible whenever one or more runners are on base.
[src:catcher/catcher] A failure to catch a ball thrown from the outfield on a play at home plate, or a failure to tag a runner, means that the defensive team fails to record an all-important out and, instead, it allows a run.
[src:catcher/catcher] On an attempt to prevent a stolen base, a catcher's bad throw might careen past the infielder and skip into the outfield, allowing an additional advance by the baserunner.
[src:catcher/catcher] Though not exactly a play, **"psyching the batter"** refers to a casual attempt by the catcher to distract the batter prior to the pitcher throwing the ball.
[src:catcher/catcher] As long as it does not fall in a lack of sportsmanship, such as offensiveness, and as long as the umpire permits it, the catcher may mention a specific throw or say something funny to try to distract the opponent to cause them to err.
[src:catcher/catcher] Because of the close mental relationship and trust that a successful pitcher must have with his catcher, a number of catchers throughout history have become preferred by pitchers, to the point that the catcher will almost always (especially during the regular season) start along with the pitcher.
[src:catcher/catcher] The catcher is then informally referred to as that pitcher's *personal catcher*.
[src:catcher/catcher] Naturally, the potential problem with this arrangement is that if the pitcher prefers to work with the team's backup catcher, then the regular catcher—presumably the better player—must be benched.
[src:catcher/catcher] However, because of the physically grueling nature of the position, many "regular" catchers are asked to either rest relatively frequently or play a different position such as first base or designated hitter.
[src:catcher/catcher] Personal catchers are often used for pitchers who specialize in throwing knuckleballs because of the difficulty of catching such an inconsistent and erratic pitch.
[src:catcher/catcher] The catcher is the most physically demanding position in baseball, more so than the pitcher.
[src:catcher/catcher] Despite being heavily padded, catchers routinely suffer some of the worst physical abuse in baseball.
[src:catcher/catcher] The catcher has the physically risky job of blocking the plate to prevent base runners from reaching home and scoring runs.
[src:catcher/catcher] Catchers also constantly get bruised and battered by pitches, foul balls, and occasionally the bat in an undisciplined follow-through of the batter's swing.
[src:catcher/catcher] Catchers also are prone to knee ailments stemming from the awkward crouching stance they assume.
[src:catcher/catcher] Prominent examples of catchers switching position (mainly first base) in mid-career include Mike Napoli, Craig Biggio, B.
[src:catcher/catcher] Surhoff, Joe Torre, Víctor Martínez, Joe Mauer, Carlos Santana, Brandon Inge, and Dale Murphy (although Murphy was also known as a poor thrower to the pitcher and to second base, nearly hitting pitchers in the process).
[src:catcher/catcher] As a result, catchers often have shorter careers than players at other positions; consequently, few catchers hold batting records that require many seasons of play to compile.
[src:catcher/catcher] Mike Piazza is the only catcher in history with more than 400 career home runs, and no catcher has amassed 3,000 career hits (Iván Rodríguez leads all Major League catchers with 2,844 hits).
[src:catcher/catcher] Although 3,000 hit club member Craig Biggio played his first three full seasons as a catcher, he played his remaining sixteen seasons at second base and in the outfield.
[src:catcher/catcher] The larger or heavier the catcher, the greater the health risks associated with repeatedly assuming a crouching or squatting position; knees and backs are especially vulnerable to "wear-and-tear" injuries.
[src:catcher/catcher] Catchers also have an increased risk of circulatory abnormalities in the catching hand.
[src:catcher/catcher] A study of minor-league ballplayers showed that, of 36 players in various positions, all nine of the catchers had hand pain during a game, and several had chronic pain in the catching hand.
[src:catcher/catcher] Catching high-speed pitches can, in some cases, cause the index finger on the gloved hand to swell to twice the size of the other fingers.
[src:catcher/catcher] Ultrasound and blood-pressure tests showed altered blood flow in the gloved hand of five of the catchers, a far higher incidence than in the hands of players at other baseball positions.
[src:catcher/catcher] In addition to their protective equipment, a catcher usually also adopts practices that minimize the risk of injury.
[src:catcher/catcher] For instance, unlike fielders elsewhere on the field, a catcher tries, to the extent possible, to catch the ball with their gloved hand alone.
[src:catcher/catcher] An outfielder may catch a fly ball by covering the ball, once it strikes the pocket of their glove, with their bare hand in order to secure it.
[src:catcher/catcher] The catcher, however, tries to keep their bare hand, which is highly vulnerable to injury, out of harm's way by presenting the pitcher with a target (the large round glove) while hiding their unprotected throwing hand behind their back or ankle.
[src:catcher/catcher] By doing so, the bare hand cannot be struck by a foul tip.
[src:catcher/catcher] Many broken fingers, split fingernails, and grotesque dislocations are avoided by adherence to this simple expedient.
[src:catcher/catcher] Given the physical punishment suffered by catchers, the pieces of equipment associated with the position are often referred to as "the tools of ignorance".
[src:catcher/catcher] This is an ironic expression; the catcher typically has the most thorough understanding of baseball tactics and strategies of any player on a team.
[src:catcher/catcher] Catchers often experience knee tendinitis because of the constant squatting and bending of the knees while catching.
[src:catcher/catcher] As of 2024, twenty men who played primarily as catchers have been inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame, in Cooperstown, New York.
[src:catcher/catcher] Catchers are also represented in a number of other Baseball Halls of Fame around the world, such as in the Canadian Baseball Hall of Fame or the Japanese Baseball Hall of Fame.
